HOUSE RESOLUTION NO. 120
BY REPRESENTATIVE FIRMENT
A RESOLUTION
To express the condolences of the House of Representatives on the death of Clarence
Durham, the last living LaSalle Parish World War II veteran.
WHEREAS, it is with immense sadness and profound regret that the House of
Representatives of the Legislature of Louisiana has learned of the passing, on March 18,
2026, of Clarence Durham, the last living LaSalle Parish World War II veteran; and
WHEREAS, Clarence Durham was born on August 16, 1927, during the height of
the Great Depression; he was the seventh-born child in his family, and he learned the value
of hard work at an early age; he left school after fifth grade to support his family and carried
his responsibilities with strength and humility; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Durham joined the military at the age of seventeen and served in
the United States Merchant Marine; he was sent to Okinawa Island, where he and forty crew
members were assigned to transport supplies, including ammunition, guns, and oil, to troops
stationed and fighting in Japan and other parts of the world; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Durham married the love of his life, Beverly Hunt, after returning
from the war; they shared sixty-two years of love and commitment to each other and raised
three sons, Gerald, Robert, and Brian; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Durham spent forty years in the oil industry and worked on drilling
rigs across many different towns and states; he lived in Abbeville, Louisiana, during this
time and eventually settled in Jena, Louisiana, in 1971; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Durham was a faithful man and longtime member of East Jena
Baptist Church; his life was grounded in his strong and steady faith, and he was known as
a devoted follower of Christ; he was also a member of the Michael Dempsey Lodge, where
he built numerous friendships and remained actively involved in the community; and
